ational junior ice hockey team|Czech Republic]]\n| [[World U17 Hockey Challenge|U17]]\n| 5th\n| 5\n| 2\n| 2\n| 4\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2003 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2003]]\n| Czech Republic\n| [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|WJC]]\n| 6th\n| 6\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 4 \n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! colspan=\"4\" | Junior totals \n! 11\n! 2\n! 3\n! 5\n! 4\n|}\n\n==Awards and honours==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Award\n! Year\n!\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Canadian Hockey League|CHL]]\n|-\n| [[CHL Top Prospects Game]]\n| [[2001-02 OHL season|2002]] \n|\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[National League A|NLA]]\n|-\n| Champion (HC Davos)\n| [[2006-07 NLA season|2007]], [[2008-09 NLA season|2009]], [[2010-11 NLA season|2011]]\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Jay Bouwmeester]] | title = [[List of Florida Panthers draft picks|Florida Panthers first round draft pick]] | years = [[2002 NHL Entry Draft|2002]] | after = [[Nathan Horton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taticek, Petr}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Czech ice hockey centres]]\n[[Category:HC Davos players]]\n[[Category:Florida Panthers draft picks]]\n[[Category:Florida Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Hershey Bears players]]\n[[Category:Houston Aeros (1994\u20132013) players]]\n[[Category:Ryt\u00ed\u0159i Kladno players]]\n[[Category:ERC Ingolstadt players]]\n[[Category:Laredo Bucks players]]\n[[Category:HC Lev Praha players]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League first round draft picks]]\n[[Category:People from Rakovn\u00edk]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Rampage players]]\n[[Category:Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds players]]\n[[Category:Wilkes-Barre/Scranton Penguins players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| caption = \n| alt = \n| image = Petr_Taticek_ERC.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| team = [[ERC Ingolstadt]]\n| league = [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga|DEL]]\n| former_teams = [[HC Kladno]]<br>[[Florida Panthers]]<br>[[HC Davos]]<br>[[HC Lev Praha]]\n| position = [[Centre (ice hockey)|Centre]]\n| shoots = Left\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 2\n| weight_lb = 190 \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|9|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Rakovn\u00edk]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| draft = 9th overall\n| draft_year = 2002\n| draft_team = [[Florida Panthers]]\n| career_start = 2000\n}}\n\n'''Petr Tat\u00ed\u010dek''' (born 22 September 1983) is a [[Czechs|Czech]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Centre (ice hockey)|centre]] currently playing for [[ERC Ingolstadt]] of the [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] (DEL). He previously played for the [[Florida Panthers]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL).\n\n==Playing career==\nTat\u00ed\u010dek was drafted ninth overall by the [[Florida Panthers]] in the [[2002 NHL Entry Draft]] from the [[Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League]] (OHL) and played just three games for the Panthers during the [[2005\u201306 NHL season]], going pointless. On 9 March 2006, Tat\u00ed\u010dek was traded to the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] in exchange for [[Richard Jackman]], but never played for them, spending the remainder of the season with their [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) affiliate, the [[Wilkes-Barre/Scranton Penguins]].\n\nTat\u00ed\u010dek then signed with the [[Washington Capitals]] as a free agent, but only played one game for their AHL affiliate, the [[Hershey Bears]], before returning to the [[Czech Extraliga]] with [[HC Kladno]]. Later in the season, he moved to [[HC Davos]] of the Swiss [[National League A|Nationalliga A]].\n\nOn 22 July 2014, Tat\u00ed\u010dek signed as a one-year contract as a free agent with [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] (DEL) club [[ERC Ingolstadt]]. On 23 November 2014, during the [[2014\u201315 DEL season|2014\u201315]] season, and having quickly adapted to the DEL and among the teams top scoring line, Tat\u00ed\u010dek was signed to a three-year contract extension to remain in Ingolstadt.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.erc-ingolstadt.de/profis/newsdetail?id=3045 | title = ERC Ingolstadt extends Taticek to 2018 | publisher = [[ERC Ingolstadt]] | date = 2014-11-23 | accessdate = 2014-11-23  | language = German}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Regular season]] \n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Playoffs]] \n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! [[Season (sports)|Season]] \n! Team \n! League \n! GP \n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]] \n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]] \n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]] \n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]] \n! GP\n! G \n! A \n! Pts \n! PIM \n|-\n| 1999\u201300\n| [[HC Kladno]]\n| Czech.20\n| 44\n| 8\n| 16\n| 24\n| 22\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1999\u20132000 Czech Extraliga season|1999\u201300]]\n| HC Kladno\n| [[Czech Extraliga|ELH]]\n| 4\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 4\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- \n| 2000\u201301\n| HC Kladno\n| Czech.20\n| 30\n| 7\n| 12\n| 19\n| 54\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2000\u201301 Czech Extraliga season|2000\u201301]]\n| HC Kladno\n| ELH\n| 3\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[2001\u201302 OHL season|2001\u201302]]\n| [[Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds]]\n| [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]]\n| 60\n| 21\n| 42\n| 63\n| 32\n| 6\n| 3\n| 3\n| 6\n| 4\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2002-03 OHL season|2002\u201303]]\n| Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds\n| OHL\n| 54\n| 12\n| 45\n| 57\n| 44\n| 4\n| 1\n| 0\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| [[2003\u201304 AHL season|2003\u201304]]\n| [[San Antonio Rampage]]\n| [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| 63\n| 4\n| 15\n| 19\n| 6\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2004\u201305 AHL season|2004\u201305]]\n| San Antonio Rampage\n| AHL\n| 67\n| 7\n| 15\n| 22\n| 21\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[2004\u201305 CHL season|2004\u201305]]\n| [[Laredo Bucks]]\n| [[Central Hockey League|CHL]]\n| 4\n| 2\n| 5\n| 7\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[2005\u201306 AHL season|2005\u201306]]\n| [[Houston Aeros (1994\u20132013)|Houston Aeros]]\n| AHL\n| 44\n| 9\n| 21\n| 30\n| 10\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306]]\n| [[Florida Panthers]]\n| [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| 3\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| 2005\u201306\n| [[Wilkes-Barre/Scranton Penguins]]\n| AHL\n| 17\n| 4\n| 4\n| 8\n| 7\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 2\n|- \n| [[2006\u201307 AHL season|2006\u201307]]\n| [[Hershey Bears]]\n| AHL\n| 1\n| 1\n| 0\n| 1\n| 2\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[2006\u201307 Czech Extraliga season|2006\u201307]]\n| HC Kladno\n| ELH\n| 10\n| 0\n| 2\n| 2\n| 6\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- \n| [[2006\u201307 NLA season|2006\u201307]]\n| [[HC Davos]]\n| [[National League A|NLA]]\n| 15\n| 4\n| 1\n| 5\n| 8\n| 17\n| 3\n| 4\n| 7\n| 10\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[2007\u201308 NLA season|2007\u201308]]\n| HC Davos\n| NLA\n| 29\n| 6\n| 2\n| 8\n| 47\n| 12\n| 1\n| 6\n| 7\n| 2\n|- \n| [[2008\u201309 NLA season|2008\u201309]]\n| HC Davos\n| NLA\n| 50\n| 6\n| 15\n| 21\n| 20\n| 21\n| 4\n| 5\n| 9\n| 12\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[2009\u201310 NLA season|2009\u201310]]\n| HC Davos\n| NLA\n| 48\n| 16\n| 19\n| 35\n| 22\n| 6\n| 3\n| 3\n| 6\n| 4\n|- \n| [[2010\u201311 NLA season|2010\u201311]]\n| HC Davos\n| NLA\n| 38\n| 14\n| 17\n| 31\n| 60\n| 14\n| 4\n| 8\n| 12\n| 4\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[2011\u201312 NLA season|2011\u201312]]\n| HC Davos\n| NLA\n| 49\n| 26\n| 15\n| 41\n| 10\n| 4\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 0\n|- \n| [[2012\u201313 NLA season|2012\u201313]]\n| HC Davos\n| NLA\n| 21\n| 5\n| 5\n| 10\n| 20\n| 5\n| 0\n| 2\n| 2\n| 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[2013\u201314 KHL season|2013\u201314]]\n| [[HC Lev Praha]]\n| [[Kontinental Hockey League|KHL]]\n| 8\n| 1\n| 1\n| 2\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- \n| [[2013\u201314 NLA season|2013\u201314]]\n| HC Davos\n| NLA\n| 4\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 2\n| 2\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 25\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[2014\u201315 DEL season|2014\u201315]]\n| [[ERC Ingolstadt]]\n| [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga|DEL]]\n| 43\n| 12\n| 28\n| 40\n| 36\n| 18\n| 4\n| 12\n| 16\n| 39\n|-\n| [[2015\u201316 DEL season|2015\u201316]]\n| ERC Ingolstadt\n| DEL\n| 44\n| 13\n| 21\n| 34\n| 24\n| 2\n| 2\n| 1\n| 3\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[2016\u201317 DEL season|2016\u201317]]\n| ERC Ingolstadt\n| DEL\n| 52\n| 13\n| 25\n| 38\n| 42\n| 2\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| [[2017\u201318 DEL season|2017\u201318]]\n| ERC Ingolstadt\n| DEL\n| 44\n| 3\n| 11\n| 14\n| 18\n| 5\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[2018\u201319 DEL season|2018\u201319]]\n| ERC Ingolstadt\n| DEL\n| 28\n| 2\n| 4\n| 6\n| 6\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" | NHL totals\n! 3\n! 0\n! 0\n! 0\n! 0\n! \u2014\n! \u2014\n! \u2014\n! \u2014\n! \u2014\n|}\n\n===International===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" ID=\"Table3\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40em\"\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! Year\n! Team\n! Event\n! Result\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|-\n| [[2000 World U-17 Hockey Challenge|2000]]\n| [[Czech Republic men's national junior ice hockey team|Czech Republic]]\n| [[World U17 Hockey Challenge|U17]]\n| 5th\n| 5\n| 2\n| 2\n| 4\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2003 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2003]]\n| Czech Republic\n| [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|WJC]]\n| 6th\n| 6\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 4 \n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! colspan=\"4\" | Junior totals \n! 11\n! 2\n! 3\n! 5\n! 4\n|}\n\n==Awards and honours==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Award\n! Year\n!\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Canadian Hockey League|CHL]]\n|-\n| [[CHL Top Prospects Game]]\n| [[2001-02 OHL season|2002]] \n|\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[National League A|NLA]]\n|-\n| Champion (HC Davos)\n| [[2006-07 NLA season|2007]], [[2008-09 NLA season|2009]], [[2010-11 NLA season|2011]]\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Jay Bouwmeester]] | title = [[List of Florida Panthers draft picks|Florida Panthers first round draft pick]] | years = [[2002 NHL Entry Draft|2002]] | after = [[Nathan Horton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taticek, Petr}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Czech ice hockey centres]]\n[[Category:HC Davos players]]\n[[Category:Florida Panthers draft picks]]\n[[Category:Florida Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Hershey Bears players]]\n[[Category:Houston Aeros (1994\u20132013) players]]\n[[Category:Ryt\u00ed\u0159i Kladno players]]\n[[Category:ERC Ingolstadt players]]\n[[Category:Laredo Bucks players]]\n[[Category:HC Lev Praha players]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League first round draft picks]]\n[[Category:People from Rakovn\u00edk]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Rampage players]]\n[[Category:Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds players]]\n[[Category:Wilkes-Barre/Scranton Penguins players]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlaying career:Typo fixing, replaced: teams top \u2192 team's top", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petr_Tat%C3%AD%C4%8Dek"}
{"title_page": "Alexa Meade", "text_new": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Alexa Meade\n| image         = Double Take-Alexa Meade.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Meade in the self-portrait ''Double Take''\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1986}}<ref name=\"glambatkinson\">Grace Lamb-Atkinson and Crispin Lopez III, [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/art/out-of-reverse-trompe-loeil-a-new-living-art/ \u201cIn Reverse Trompe L\u2019Oeil, Models Are Both Subject and Painting Surface,\u201d] [[PBS Newshour]], March 8, 2011.</ref>\n| birth_place   = Washington, D.C.\n| nationality   = American\n| field         = [[Installation art]], painting, photography\n| training      = [[Vassar College]]\n| movement      = \n| works         = ''Color of Reality'', painting in [[Ariana Grande]] music video ''[[God is a Woman]]''\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = [[TED (conference)|TED]] Speaker, [[Tribeca Film Festival]] \u2013 \"Disruptive Innovation Award\", [[Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics]] \u2013 \"Artist in Residence\"\n| signature =\n| influenced =\n| website       = {{URL|alexameade.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexa Meade''' (born 1986) is an American [[installation artist]] best known for her portraits painted directly onto the human body and inanimate objects in a way that collapses depth and makes her models appear two-dimensional when photographed. What remains is \"a photo of a painting of a person, and the real person hidden somewhere underneath.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Cole |first=Adam |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/pictureshow/2012/06/08/154507514/paintings-in-really-living-color |title=Paintings In (Really) Living Color : The Picture Show |publisher=NPR |date=June 8, 2012 |access-date=December 6, 2013}}</ref> She takes a classical concept \u2013 [[trompe l'oeil]], the art of making a two-dimensional representational painting look like a real three-dimensional space \u2013 and does the opposite, making real life appear to be a painting.<ref name=\"glambatkinson\"/><ref name=\"mmackay\">{{cite news |last=Mackay |first=Mairi |title=The artist who turns people into paintings |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/US/03/19/real.life.painting.artist/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=March 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMeade was born in Washington, D.C., and raised in [[Chevy Chase, Maryland]].<ref name=\"Wpost Flesh perspective\">{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Zak |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/23/AR2010032303850.html |title=Flesh perspective: Alexa Meade's growing body of work is work of the body |work=The Washington Post |date=March 24, 2010 |access-date=December 6, 2013}}</ref> She graduated from [[Vassar College]] in [[Poughkeepsie, New York]], in 2009, with a bachelor's degree in political science.<ref name=\"Wpost Flesh perspective\"/><ref name=\"cthomasbailey\">Carlene Thomas-Bailey, [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/aug/31/alexa-meade-living-painting-art \u201cBody art: Alexa Meade\u2019s living paintings,\u201d] ''[[The Guardian]]'', August 31, 2011.</ref><ref>Ryan Swearingen, [http://www.statedmag.com/articles/interview-artist-alexa-meade-creates-living-paintings.html# \u201cAlexa Meade,\u201d] ''Stated Magazine'', March 8, 2011.</ref> Initially planning on a path in politics,<ref name=\"lclark\">Liat Clark, [https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-10/25/alexa-meade-3d-artist \"Watch Alexa Meade\u2019s full Wired 2012 talk about art, humans and milk,\"] ''Wired'', October 25, 2012.</ref> she interned for congressmen and senators on [[Capitol Hill]], and then worked as a press assistant on [[Barack Obama]]'s 2008 presidential campaign.<ref name=\"mmackay\"/><ref name=\"Wpost Flesh perspective\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early inspiration and paintings===\n[[File:Blueprint Installation-Alexa Meade.jpg|thumbnail|right|Painting one of her living subjects]]\n\nIn 2009, an assignment in an elective art class at [[Vassar College]] sparked Meade's curiosity. She decided to explore space and light through the idea of putting black paint on the ground where the shadows were cast. She later expanded the concept by making a [[grayscale]] \"mapping of light\" with paint on the human body. In so doing, she realized that she had made the three-dimensional form appear to be a two-dimensional painting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/alexa-meade-3d-artist|title=Watch Alexa Meade's full Wired 2012 talk about art, humans and milk|first=Liat|last=Clark|date=January 2, 2013|publisher=|access-date=March 4, 2019|via=www.wired.co.uk}}</ref>\nThe results of these experiments changed her perspective and inspired her to reevaluate her career goals. Despite having grown up surrounded by the political culture of Washington D.C. and initially planning to enter that field herself, as Meade says, \u201cI just felt like even though this was supposed to be my dream, it didn\u2019t quite fit with who I thought I was on the inside.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.24life.com/seeing-more-dimensions-in-color-and-life/|title=Seeing More Dimensions \u2013 In Color, and Life|author=|date=January 5, 2017|website=24life.com|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, she honed her technique in her parents\u2019 Washington, D.C. basement by\npracticing painting on inanimate objects including grapefruits, fried eggs and sausage.<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/03/06/tech/web/artist-painting-alexa-meade/index.html|title=People-painter turns tables on illusion|first=Natalie |last=Angley|date=|website=CNN|accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref> She has credited her lack of formal art training with allowing her to come up with unique ideas of surfaces she could paint on, since she didn't think of painting as something that necessarily had\nto be done on a canvas.<ref name=\"thegreatdiscontent.com\">https://thegreatdiscontent.com/interview/alexa-meade</ref>\n\nMeade first gained public recognition in March 2010, when her living paintings went viral following a short post about her work on [[Jason Kottke]]'s blog kottke.org.<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/> She soon received coverage on [[CNN]] and elsewhere.<ref name=\"mmackay\"/> Her website went from having negligible views to an estimated 30,000-page views the next day.<ref name=\"nalk\">Nell Alk, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303901504577460742319149810 \u201cThe Artist in Action,\u201d] ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', June 11, 2012.</ref> Her most famous artwork at the time, \"Transit,\" features an older man Meade painted on in her basement studio, and then photographed riding the Washington, D.C. metro, looking \"as if a painting from the [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] has leapt off its wall to go walking through the flesh-and-blood world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2011/08/alexa-meade-makes-human-models-look-like-walking-paintings.html|title=An Artist Who Makes Real People Look Like Paintings|first=Heather|last=Murphy|date=August 16, 2011|website=Slate Magazine|accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Her speech at the 2013 [[TEDGlobal]] conference in [[Edinburgh, Scotland|Edinburgh]], Scotland, \"Your Body is my Canvas,\" offers a behind the scenes look at her work, and details her career beginnings. She has named installation artist [[Robert Irwin (artist)|Robert Irwin]] as an inspiration, citing his biography, ''Seeing is Forgetting the Name of the Thing One Sees'', as an influence on how she thinks about the perception of space.<ref name=\"Frank\">{{cite news |last=Frank |first=Priscilla |title=Alexa Meade's Incredible Painted Photographs |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/12/alexa-meade_n_1587703.html |newspaper=HuffPost |date=June 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics===\n\nIn 2015, Meade was invited to be Artist-in-Residence at the Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics in [[Waterloo, Ontario]]. For this interdisciplinary project, Meade was given free rein to pursue a period of self-directed study of [[theoretical physics|theoretical]] and [[quantum physics]], and in return she created a collaborative art installation piece with the researchers.  The curator of the artist-in-residence program, cited Meade's \"fearlessness\" as vital to collaboration, stating \"She's not one to shy away from asking questions, which created a wonderful synergy between the creative and scientific thought processes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.perimeterinstitute.ca/living-chalkboard|title=The Living Chalkboard - Perimeter Institute|author=|date=|website=www.perimeterinstitute.ca|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.perimeterinstitute.ca/node/97271|title=Watch this chalkboard come to life - Perimeter Institute|author=|date=|website=www.perimeterinstitute.ca|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''Color of Reality''===\nColor of Reality\nIn 2016, Meade painted dancers [[Jon Boogz]] and [[Lil Buck]] for the short film ''Color of Reality'' produced by [[Animi Design]]. Color of Reality explores a story about [[gun violence]] and [[racism|racial tensions in America]] as expressed through painting and dance. Dancer Lil Buck performed his unique style of dancing called [[Memphis Jookin\u2019]], which is a combination of ballet and [[street dancing]]. The short film was critically acclaimed in the press, with ''[[The New York Times]]'' art critic Gia Kourlas writing: \u201cThink of it as a van Gogh \u2014 that is, if one of his paintings were brought to life as a performative protest.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/19/arts/dance/lil-buck-and-jon-boogz-wearing-paint-as-they-tell-a-tale.html|title=Lil Buck and Jon Boogz, Wearing Paint as They Tell a Tale|first=Gia|last=Kourlas|date=September 18, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=March 4, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The film was screened at [[Lincoln Center]], the [[Apollo Theater]], and the [[Hammer Museum]]. It won [[CNN]] Great Big Story's Art as Impact Award, and was included in the [[National Civil Rights Museum]]\u2019s Freedom Awards Ceremony.\n\n===Ariana Grande: ''[[God Is a Woman]]''===\nIn 2018 Meade painted on singer [[Ariana Grande]] for her music video ''[[God Is a Woman]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kHLHSlExFis|title=Ariana Grande - God is a woman|first=|last=ArianaGrandeVevo|date=July 13, 2018|publisher=|access-date=March 4, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref> Grande\u2019s music video director Dave Meyers had seen Meade and [[Sheila Vand\u2019s]] project ''Milk: What Will You Make of Me?'' (in which Vand, bodypainted by Meade, lay in a tub of milk, the colors of the paint eventually dispersing and creating patterns throughout the milk) and approached both artists with the idea of bodypainting Grande in a milky pool of paint.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/style-beauty/beauty/a22370053/alexa-meade-ariana-grande-naked-body-painter-interview/|title=What It Was Like Body-Painting a Nearly Naked Ariana Grande for Her \"God Is a Woman\" Music Video|first=Jasmine|last=Ting|date=July 19, 2018|website=Cosmopolitan|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> The piece shows Grande, nude except for Meade\u2019s paint in shades of lavender, blue and white, floating in a pool as the colors swirl around her. [[Allure magazine|Allure]] called it \"Some of the most gorgeous imagery...striking, empowering.\" Meade's painted aesthetic set off a beauty and makeup trend, as thousands of people created inspired tribute art.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/ariana-grande-god-is-a-woman-makeup-looks|title=You Have to See These \u201cGod Is a Woman\u201d-Inspired Makeup Looks|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|date=|website=Teen Vogue|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other projects===\nIn 2010, Meade\u2019s work was exhibited at the [[Saatchi Gallery]] in London.<ref name=\"wp\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/23/AR2010032303850.html   Washington Post: Flesh perspective: Alexa Meade's growing body of work is work of the body]</ref> In 2012, Meade created a live performance at the [[Smithsonian National Portrait Gallery]] in Washington, D.C. for the exhibit ''Camera-Ready Color.''<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303901504577460742319149810|title=The Artist in Action|first=Nell|last=Alk|date=June 12, 2012|publisher=|access-date=March 4, 2019|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref> In 2013, she gave a speech at the [[TEDGlobal]] conference in Edinburgh, Scotland, ''Your Body is my Canvas'', in which she offered a behind the scenes look at her work and described the beginning of her career in detail.<ref name=\"thegreatdiscontent.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://petapixel.com/2013/11/14/alexa-meade-began-turning-people-3d-paintings/|title=Alexa Meade on Why and How She Began Turning People Into Real Life Paintings|author=|date=|website=petapixel.com|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> In 2014, she joined the musician [[Avicii]] and others as part of the ''Project Warehouse'' campaign for Denim & Supply. As part of the project, she painted large-scale public art installations in Madrid, Santa Monica and Toronto.<ref>Apostolos Mitsios, [http://www.hgissue.com/new/denim-supply-brings-its-warehouse-project-featuring-artist-alexa-meade-to-madrid/ \u201cDenim & Supply Brings Its Warehouse Project, Featuring Artist Alexa Meade, to Madrid,\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034205/http://www.hgissue.com/new/denim-supply-brings-its-warehouse-project-featuring-artist-alexa-meade-to-madrid/ |date=December 1, 2017 }} ''HG'', September 19, 2014.</ref><ref>Rashad Webb, [http://www.essentialhommemag.com/denim-supply-ralph-lauren-teams-up-with-music-and-art-visionaries-to-present-project-warehouse/ \u201cDenim & Supply Ralph Lauren Teams Up With Music and Art Visionaries to Present Project Warehouse,\u201d] ''Essential Homme'', August 4, 2014.</ref> In 2015, Meade created several artworks in Paris, France, including exhibitions at the [[Grand Palais]] and the [[Pinacoth\u00e8que de Paris]], and a live performance at [[David Lynch]]'s nightclub Silencio. In 2015, she was artist-in-residence at the Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics in Waterloo, Canada, and created an installation piece inspired by the scientists' work. In 2016 at the Q3 Symposium and Lecture on Peace and Security in a Quantum Age held in Sydney, Australia, Meade joined quantum physicists and scholars to debate the political, ethical and philosophical implications of [[quantum computing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sydney.edu.au/news-opinion/news/2016/02/05/probing-the-peace-and-security-implications-of-quantum-innovatio.html|title=Probing the peace and security implications of quantum innovation|author=|date=|website=The University of Sydney|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Also in 2016, Meade was invited to the [[White House]] under [[President Barack Obama]] for the South by South Lawn (SXSL) event showcasing creators and innovators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/sxsl/|title=South by South Lawn (SXSL)|author=|date=|website=sxsw.com|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> In 2017, Meade went on tour with [[Refinery29]]\u2019s installation exhibit ''29Rooms''.<ref name=\"29 rooms\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/home/la-hm-refinery29-29rooms-20171201-htmlstory.html|title=The good news: Refinery 29's popular 29 Rooms hits DTLA Thursday. The bad news: It's sold out|first=Lisa|last=Boone|date=|website=latimes.com|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Also in 2016 she created the film ''Color of Reality'' with dance artists Jon Boogz and [[Lil Buck]]. In 2017, Meade was honored by the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] with the [[Disruptive Innovation Award]], an honor celebrating those who \"inspire and empower people towards innovative thinking and creative activism\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/3dxzj3/alexa-meade-body-painting-artist-disrupting-portraiture|title=Meet the Body Painting Artist Disrupting Portraiture|first=Kara|last=Weisenstein|date=May 4, 2017|website=vice.com|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Her exhibition ''Immersed in Wonderland'' in Beverly Hills was attended by 40, 000 visitors in 2018. In 2018-2019, she was a keynote lecturer at [[Stanford University]] for Celebration of Mind, a colloquium about the intersection of math, magic, and art.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arts.stanford.edu/event/79726/|title=A Celebration of Mind: Mathematics, Art, and Magic \u2013 Stanford Arts|first1=\u00a9 Stanford|last1=University|first2=|last2=Stanford|first3=California 94305 Copyright|last3=Complaints|date=|website=stanford.edu|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://arts.stanford.edu/event/84877/   Stanford Arts Lectures (October, 2019)]</ref>Meade also lectured at Princeton University in the Computer Science Department on the subject \"Painting in More Dimensions\".<ref>[https://www.cs.princeton.edu/events/25887   Princeton University/Department of Computer Science: Painting in More Dimensions]</ref>  Meade was selected by [[Google Arts & Culture]], guided by [[Frida Kahlo]]\u2019s great-niece, [[Cristina Kahlo]], to create artwork for \"Faces of Frida\" celebrating the famed Mexican portrait painter's life and her legacy carried on by women today.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://artsandculture.google.com/theme/UgJiy6dfuVDsKw|title=Making \"Frida & I\": Capturing Frida Kahlo\u2019s Legacy On Film|author=|date=|website=Google Arts & Culture|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/veronicavillafane/2018/05/23/google-unveils-frida-kahlo-retrospective-with-never-before-seen-artifacts/|title=Google Unveils Frida Kahlo Retrospective With Never-Before-Seen Artifacts|first=Veronica|last=Villafa\u00f1e|date=|website=Forbes|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>Alexa was Artist-In-Residence at Google where she collaborated on an installation with engineers developing Light Field technology.<ref>[https://www.wired.com/story/alexa-meade-art/  Wired: How Painter Alexa Meade Creates Dimension-Collapsing Art]</ref>\n\nAlexa Meade's art is still a subject of research and terminology development. In August, 2019, [[Scientific American]] wrote: \"\u201cMeade\u2019s unique work illustrates that depth perception is always a brain construct, not only in art but also in life. Because our retinas are fundamentally flat surfaces, our neurons must infer the third dimension from cues such as shadows, perspective lines or the relative sizes of objects\u2014both in paintings and in everyday perception. Meade\u2019s artful application of paint disrupts this brain process.\u201d<ref>[https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/illusion-chasers/when-a-still-life-comes-alive/  Scientific American: Illusion Chasers. When a Still Life Comes Alive]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|26em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://alexameade.com/ Official website]\n* {{Commons category-inline|Alexa Meade}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meade, Alexa}}\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:American women installation artists]]\n[[Category:American installation artists]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Painters from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Vassar College alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Alexa Meade\n| image         = Double Take-Alexa Meade.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Meade in the self-portrait ''Double Take''\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1986}}<ref name=\"glambatkinson\">Grace Lamb-Atkinson and Crispin Lopez III, [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/art/out-of-reverse-trompe-loeil-a-new-living-art/ \u201cIn Reverse Trompe L\u2019Oeil, Models Are Both Subject and Painting Surface,\u201d] [[PBS Newshour]], March 8, 2011.</ref>\n| birth_place   = Washington, D.C.\n| nationality   = American\n| field         = [[Installation art]], painting, photography\n| training      = [[Vassar College]]\n| movement      = \n| works         = ''Color of Reality'', painting in [[Ariana Grande]] music video ''[[God is a Woman]]''\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = [[TED (conference)|TED]] Speaker, [[Tribeca Film Festival]] \u2013 \"Disruptive Innovation Award\", [[Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics]] \u2013 \"Artist in Residence\"\n| signature =\n| influenced =\n| website       = {{URL|alexameade.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexa Meade''' (born 1986) is an American [[installation artist]] best known for her portraits painted directly onto the human body and inanimate objects in a way that collapses depth and makes her models appear two-dimensional when photographed. What remains is \"a photo of a painting of a person, and the real person hidden somewhere underneath.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Cole |first=Adam |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/pictureshow/2012/06/08/154507514/paintings-in-really-living-color |title=Paintings In (Really) Living Color : The Picture Show |publisher=NPR |date=June 8, 2012 |access-date=December 6, 2013}}</ref> She takes a classical concept \u2013 [[trompe l'oeil]], the art of making a two-dimensional representational painting look like a real three-dimensional space \u2013 and does the opposite, making real life appear to be a painting.<ref name=\"glambatkinson\"/><ref name=\"mmackay\">{{cite news |last=Mackay |first=Mairi |title=The artist who turns people into paintings |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/US/03/19/real.life.painting.artist/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=March 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMeade was born in Washington, D.C., and raised in [[Chevy Chase, Maryland]].<ref name=\"Wpost Flesh perspective\">{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Zak |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/23/AR2010032303850.html |title=Flesh perspective: Alexa Meade's growing body of work is work of the body |work=The Washington Post |date=March 24, 2010 |access-date=December 6, 2013}}</ref> She graduated from [[Vassar College]] in [[Poughkeepsie, New York]], in 2009, with a bachelor's degree in political science.<ref name=\"Wpost Flesh perspective\"/><ref name=\"cthomasbailey\">Carlene Thomas-Bailey, [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/aug/31/alexa-meade-living-painting-art \u201cBody art: Alexa Meade\u2019s living paintings,\u201d] ''[[The Guardian]]'', August 31, 2011.</ref><ref>Ryan Swearingen, [http://www.statedmag.com/articles/interview-artist-alexa-meade-creates-living-paintings.html# \u201cAlexa Meade,\u201d] ''Stated Magazine'', March 8, 2011.</ref> Initially planning on a path in politics,<ref name=\"lclark\">Liat Clark, [https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-10/25/alexa-meade-3d-artist \"Watch Alexa Meade\u2019s full Wired 2012 talk about art, humans and milk,\"] ''Wired'', October 25, 2012.</ref> she interned for congressmen and senators on [[Capitol Hill]], and then worked as a press assistant on [[Barack Obama]]'s 2008 presidential campaign.<ref name=\"mmackay\"/><ref name=\"Wpost Flesh perspective\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early inspiration and paintings===\n[[File:Blueprint Installation-Alexa Meade.jpg|thumbnail|right|Painting one of her living subjects]]\n\nIn 2009, an assignment in an elective art class at [[Vassar College]] sparked Meade's curiosity. She decided to explore space and light through the idea of putting black paint on the ground where the shadows were cast. She later expanded the concept by making a [[grayscale]] \"mapping of light\" with paint on the human body. In so doing, she realized that she had made the three-dimensional form appear to be a two-dimensional painting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/alexa-meade-3d-artist|title=Watch Alexa Meade's full Wired 2012 talk about art, humans and milk|first=Liat|last=Clark|date=January 2, 2013|publisher=|access-date=March 4, 2019|via=www.wired.co.uk}}</ref>\nThe results of these experiments changed her perspective and inspired her to reevaluate her career goals. Despite having grown up surrounded by the political culture of Washington D.C. and initially planning to enter that field herself, as Meade says, \u201cI just felt like even though this was supposed to be my dream, it didn\u2019t quite fit with who I thought I was on the inside.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.24life.com/seeing-more-dimensions-in-color-and-life/|title=Seeing More Dimensions \u2013 In Color, and Life|author=|date=January 5, 2017|website=24life.com|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, she honed her technique in her parents\u2019 Washington, D.C. basement by\npracticing painting on inanimate objects including grapefruits, fried eggs and sausage.<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/03/06/tech/web/artist-painting-alexa-meade/index.html|title=People-painter turns tables on illusion|first=Natalie |last=Angley|date=|website=CNN|accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref> She has credited her lack of formal art training with allowing her to come up with unique ideas of surfaces she could paint on, since she didn't think of painting as something that necessarily had\nto be done on a canvas.<ref name=\"thegreatdiscontent.com\">https://thegreatdiscontent.com/interview/alexa-meade</ref>\n\nMeade first gained public recognition in March 2010, when her living paintings went viral following a short post about her work on [[Jason Kottke]]'s blog kottke.org.<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/> She soon received coverage on [[CNN]] and elsewhere.<ref name=\"mmackay\"/> Her website went from having negligible views to an estimated 30,000-page views the next day.<ref name=\"nalk\">Nell Alk, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303901504577460742319149810 \u201cThe Artist in Action,\u201d] ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', June 11, 2012.</ref> Her most famous artwork at the time, \"Transit,\" features an older man Meade painted on in her basement studio, and then photographed riding the Washington, D.C. metro, looking \"as if a painting from the [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] has leapt off its wall to go walking through the flesh-and-blood world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2011/08/alexa-meade-makes-human-models-look-like-walking-paintings.html|title=An Artist Who Makes Real People Look Like Paintings|first=Heather|last=Murphy|date=August 16, 2011|website=Slate Magazine|accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Her speech at the 2013 [[TEDGlobal]] conference in [[Edinburgh, Scotland|Edinburgh]], Scotland, \"Your Body is my Canvas,\" offers a behind the scenes look at her work, and details her career beginnings. She has named installation artist [[Robert Irwin (artist)|Robert Irwin]] as an inspiration, citing his biography, ''Seeing is Forgetting the Name of the Thing One Sees'', as an influence on how she thinks about the perception of space.<ref name=\"Frank\">{{cite news |last=Frank |first=Priscilla |title=Alexa Meade's Incredible Painted Photographs |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/12/alexa-meade_n_1587703.html |newspaper=HuffPost |date=June 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics===\n\nIn 2015, Meade was invited to be Artist-in-Residence at the Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics in [[Waterloo, Ontario]]. For this interdisciplinary project, Meade was given free rein to pursue a period of self-directed study of [[theoretical physics|theoretical]] and [[quantum physics]], and in return she created a collaborative art installation piece with the researchers.  The curator of the artist-in-residence program, cited Meade's \"fearlessness\" as vital to collaboration, stating \"She's not one to shy away from asking questions, which created a wonderful synergy between the creative and scientific thought processes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.perimeterinstitute.ca/living-chalkboard|title=The Living Chalkboard - Perimeter Institute|author=|date=|website=www.perimeterinstitute.ca|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.perimeterinstitute.ca/node/97271|title=Watch this chalkboard come to life - Perimeter Institute|author=|date=|website=www.perimeterinstitute.ca|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''Color of Reality''===\nColor of Reality\nIn 2016, Meade painted dancers [[Jon Boogz]] and [[Lil Buck]] for the short film ''Color of Reality'' produced by [[Animi Design]]. Color of Reality explores a story about [[gun violence]] and [[racism|racial tensions in America]] as expressed through painting and dance. Dancer Lil Buck performed his unique style of dancing called [[Memphis Jookin\u2019]], which is a combination of ballet and [[street dancing]]. The short film was critically acclaimed in the press, with ''[[The New York Times]]'' art critic Gia Kourlas writing: \u201cThink of it as a van Gogh \u2014 that is, if one of his paintings were brought to life as a performative protest.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/19/arts/dance/lil-buck-and-jon-boogz-wearing-paint-as-they-tell-a-tale.html|title=Lil Buck and Jon Boogz, Wearing Paint as They Tell a Tale|first=Gia|last=Kourlas|date=September 18, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=March 4, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The film was screened at [[Lincoln Center]], the [[Apollo Theater]], and the [[Hammer Museum]]. It won [[CNN]] Great Big Story's Art as Impact Award, and was included in the [[National Civil Rights Museum]]\u2019s Freedom Awards Ceremony.\n\n===Ariana Grande: ''[[God Is a Woman]]''===\nIn 2018 Meade painted on singer [[Ariana Grande]] for her music video ''[[God Is a Woman]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kHLHSlExFis|title=Ariana Grande - God is a woman|first=|last=ArianaGrandeVevo|date=July 13, 2018|publisher=|access-date=March 4, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref> Grande\u2019s music video director Dave Meyers had seen Meade and [[Sheila Vand\u2019s]] project ''Milk: What Will You Make of Me?'' (in which Vand, bodypainted by Meade, lay in a tub of milk, the colors of the paint eventually dispersing and creating patterns throughout the milk) and approached both artists with the idea of bodypainting Grande in a milky pool of paint.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/style-beauty/beauty/a22370053/alexa-meade-ariana-grande-naked-body-painter-interview/|title=What It Was Like Body-Painting a Nearly Naked Ariana Grande for Her \"God Is a Woman\" Music Video|first=Jasmine|last=Ting|date=July 19, 2018|website=Cosmopolitan|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> The piece shows Grande, nude except for Meade\u2019s paint in shades of lavender, blue and white, floating in a pool as the colors swirl around her. [[Allure magazine|Allure]] called it \"Some of the most gorgeous imagery...striking, empowering.\" Meade's painted aesthetic set off a beauty and makeup trend, as thousands of people created inspired tribute art.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/ariana-grande-god-is-a-woman-makeup-looks|title=You Have to See These \u201cGod Is a Woman\u201d-Inspired Makeup Looks|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|date=|website=Teen Vogue|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other projects===\nIn 2010, Meade\u2019s work was exhibited at the [[Saatchi Gallery]] in London.<ref name=\"wp\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com//wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/23/AR2010032303850.html   Washington Post: Flesh perspective: Alexa Meade's growing body of work is work of the body]</ref> In 2012, Meade created a live performance at the [[Smithsonian National Portrait Gallery]] in Washington, D.C. for the exhibit ''Camera-Ready Color.''<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303901504577460742319149810|title=The Artist in Action|first=Nell|last=Alk|date=June 12, 2012|publisher=|access-date=March 4, 2019|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref> In 2013, she gave a speech at the [[TEDGlobal]] conference in Edinburgh, Scotland, ''Your Body is my Canvas'', in which she offered a behind the scenes look at her work and described the beginning of her career in detail.<ref name=\"thegreatdiscontent.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://petapixel.com/2013/11/14/alexa-meade-began-turning-people-3d-paintings/|title=Alexa Meade on Why and How She Began Turning People Into Real Life Paintings|author=|date=|website=petapixel.com|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> In 2014, she joined the musician [[Avicii]] and others as part of the ''Project Warehouse'' campaign for Denim & Supply. As part of the project, she painted large-scale public art installations in Madrid, Santa Monica and Toronto.<ref>Apostolos Mitsios, [http://www.hgissue.com/new/denim-supply-brings-its-warehouse-project-featuring-artist-alexa-meade-to-madrid/ \u201cDenim & Supply Brings Its Warehouse Project, Featuring Artist Alexa Meade, to Madrid,\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034205/http://www.hgissue.com/new/denim-supply-brings-its-warehouse-project-featuring-artist-alexa-meade-to-madrid/ |date=December 1, 2017 }} ''HG'', September 19, 2014.</ref><ref>Rashad Webb, [http://www.essentialhommemag.com/denim-supply-ralph-lauren-teams-up-with-music-and-art-visionaries-to-present-project-warehouse/ \u201cDenim & Supply Ralph Lauren Teams Up With Music and Art Visionaries to Present Project Warehouse,\u201d] ''Essential Homme'', August 4, 2014.</ref> In 2015, Meade created several artworks in Paris, France, including exhibitions at the [[Grand Palais]] and the [[Pinacoth\u00e8que de Paris]], and a live performance at [[David Lynch]]'s nightclub Silencio. In 2015, she was artist-in-residence at the Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics in Waterloo, Canada, and created an installation piece inspired by the scientists' work. In 2016 at the Q3 Symposium and Lecture on Peace and Security in a Quantum Age held in Sydney, Australia, Meade joined quantum physicists and scholars to debate the political, ethical and philosophical implications of [[quantum computing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sydney.edu.au/news-opinion/news/2016/02/05/probing-the-peace-and-security-implications-of-quantum-innovatio.html|title=Probing the peace and security implications of quantum innovation|author=|date=|website=The University of Sydney|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Also in 2016, Meade was invited to the [[White House]] under [[President Barack Obama]] for the South by South Lawn (SXSL) event showcasing creators and innovators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/sxsl/|title=South by South Lawn (SXSL)|author=|date=|website=sxsw.com|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> In 2017, Meade went on tour with [[Refinery29]]\u2019s installation exhibit ''29Rooms''.<ref name=\"29 rooms\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/home/la-hm-refinery29-29rooms-20171201-htmlstory.html|title=The good news: Refinery 29's popular 29 Rooms hits DTLA Thursday. The bad news: It's sold out|first=Lisa|last=Boone|date=|website=latimes.com|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Also in 2016 she created the film ''Color of Reality'' with dance artists Jon Boogz and [[Lil Buck]]. In 2017, Meade was honored by the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] with the [[Disruptive Innovation Award]], an honor celebrating those who \"inspire and empower people towards innovative thinking and creative activism\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/3dxzj3/alexa-meade-body-painting-artist-disrupting-portraiture|title=Meet the Body Painting Artist Disrupting Portraiture|first=Kara|last=Weisenstein|date=May 4, 2017|website=vice.com|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> Her exhibition ''Immersed in Wonderland'' in Beverly Hills was attended by 40, 000 visitors in 2018. In 2018-2019, she was a keynote lecturer at [[Stanford University]] for Celebration of Mind, a colloquium about the intersection of math, magic, and art.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arts.stanford.edu/event/79726/|title=A Celebration of Mind: Mathematics, Art, and Magic \u2013 Stanford Arts|first1=\u00a9 Stanford|last1=University|first2=|last2=Stanford|first3=California 94305 Copyright|last3=Complaints|date=|website=stanford.edu|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://arts.stanford.edu/event/84877/   Stanford Arts Lectures (October, 2019)]</ref>Meade also lectured at Princeton University in the Computer Science Department on the subject \"Painting in More Dimensions\".<ref>[https://www.cs.princeton.edu/events/25887   Princeton University/Department of Computer Science: Painting in More Dimensions]</ref>  Meade was selected by [[Google Arts & Culture]], guided by [[Frida Kahlo]]\u2019s great-niece, [[Cristina Kahlo]], to create artwork for \"Faces of Frida\" celebrating the famed Mexican portrait painter's life and her legacy carried on by women today.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://artsandculture.google.com/theme/UgJiy6dfuVDsKw|title=Making \"Frida & I\": Capturing Frida Kahlo\u2019s Legacy On Film|author=|date=|website=Google Arts & Culture|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/veronicavillafane/2018/05/23/google-unveils-frida-kahlo-retrospective-with-never-before-seen-artifacts/|title=Google Unveils Frida Kahlo Retrospective With Never-Before-Seen Artifacts|first=Veronica|last=Villafa\u00f1e|date=|website=Forbes|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>Alexa was Artist-In-Residence at Google where she collaborated on an installation with engineers developing Light Field technology.<ref>[https://www.wired.com/story/alexa-meade-art/  Wired: How Painter Alexa Meade Creates Dimension-Collapsing Art]</ref>\n\nAlexa Meade's art is still a subject of research and terminology development. In August, 2019, [[Scientific American]] wrote: \"\u201cMeade\u2019s unique work illustrates that depth perception is always a brain construct, not only in art but also in life. Because our retinas are fundamentally flat surfaces, our neurons must infer the third dimension from cues such as shadows, perspective lines or the relative sizes of objects\u2014both in paintings and in everyday perception. Meade\u2019s artful application of paint disrupts this brain process.\u201d<ref>[https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/illusion-chasers/when-a-still-life-comes-alive/  Scientific American: Illusion Chasers. When a Still Life Comes Alive]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|26em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://alexameade.com/ Official website]\n* {{Commons category-inline|Alexa Meade}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meade, Alexa}}\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:American women installation artists]]\n[[Category:American installation artists]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Painters from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Vassar College alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "DemonDays64", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing bot mistake (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexa_Meade"}
